### Angular Folder Structure
Essentially what you need to know is that all of your Typescript, HTML, and CSS files go into ```/src/app```.

```app.component.ts``` is your main Typscript file.
```app.component.html``` is your main HTML file.
```app.component.css``` is your main CSS file. 

I would recommend that you do all of your checking in these files.

### About Component Files

Everything in Angular is based on components (usually files are named like ```<filename>.component.ts```). If you start with a basic exported typescript class, to make it an Angular component, you utilize the ```@Component``` decorator:

 1] "selector" - this is how you can call the component in an HTML tag. In this case your HTML tag would be<app-root>.
 2] "templteUrl" - your reference location to the component HTML file.
 3] "styleUrls" - your reference to the CSS file.

Alternatively, Angular automatically creates components in the command line with "ng generate component <component name>", so you really never manually create a component class.

```
@Component({
  selector: 'app-root',
  templateUrl: './app.component.html',
  styleUrls: ['./app.component.scss']
})
export class AppComponent { ... }```
```

### Services
In the project I linked above, I created a service component that should hold all the methods that will interact with the Truffle Smart Contract. In Angular, service components are decorated with ```@Injectable```. 

When you want to use your Angular service, you must "inject" it into your component (as aforementioned) class. This looks like:

```
import { Component } from '@angular/core';
// STEP 1: Import your Angular Service
import { Web3serviceService } from "./services/web3/web3service.service";

@Component({
  selector: 'app-root',
  templateUrl: './app.component.html',
  styleUrls: ['./app.component.scss']
})
export class AppComponent {
  
  // STEP 2: "Inject" your service in the constructor.
  constructor(private web3Service: Web3serviceService) {

    // STEP 3: Now your service class is instantiated and you can call its methods
    let value = web3Service.getEtherBalance(this.account);

  }
```

## Start the Angular Project

In the root directory, just use ```npm start``` to run the project. Will be at ```http://localhost:4200```
